<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Alarcon Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1803191894 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1522 GMT 17 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1803191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Raimundo Lopez] </F>
  [Text] Havana, 17 Mar (PL) -- Ricardo Alarcon, president of 
the National Assembly of the People's Government, said today 
that thousands of proposals from workers are being implemented 
to clean up the internal finances of the country. 
  In statements to PRENSA LATINA, Alarcon explained that this 
is one of the main results of the consultation with the labor 
union rank and file to seek alternatives for the recovery of the 
national economy. 
  That process, initiated under the leadership of the Cuban 
Workers Federation at the end of last January, concluded this 
Wednesday after some 80,000 assemblies attended by more than 3 
million persons were held at the work centers. 
  The workers assemblies, Alarcon said, have served to discuss 
collectively the possible general measures. The assemblies have 
permitted each worker to express his opinions and discuss them 
along with the opinions of others, so as to form a collective 
consensus. 
  I think they have been useful in creating consensus behind 
specific actions to be launched at the national level, Alarcon 
stressed. 
  The legislative leader asserted that this aspect is as 
important as the identification in each work center of the 
problems and the decisions that are necessary "to immediately 
reduce costs and improve efficiency." 
  From this point of view, Alarcon continued, thousands of 
proposals and specific measures have been positively identified 
and have materialized. Many of these measures are already being 
implemented; they are being executed. 
  Since losing its former socialist bloc commercial partners, 
Cuba has faced an adverse economic situation, which in financial 
terms is expressed in an excess of currency amounting to over 10 
billion pesos -- equal to the U.S. dollar at the official 
exchange rate -- a 4.2-billion-peso fiscal deficit, and high 
subsidies. 
  This situation deteriorated further as a result of the 
tightening of the blockade the United States imposed on the 
island more than three decades ago, which authorities estimate 
has caused losses amounting to at least $40 billion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

