<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaviria Temporarily Alleviates Labor Ministry Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2103163394 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2203 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2103163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 19 Mar (DPA) -- Today, Colombian 
President Cesar Gaviria temporarily overcame the ministerial 
crisis that arose last night when Labor Minister Luis Fernando 
Ramirez, who was proclaimed vice presidential candidate by the 
Conservative Party, resigned. 
  According to the text of a presidential decree issued today 
and given to DPA, Gaviria entrusted the ministry to Deputy 
Minister Gerardo Hernandez. A labor minister is expected to be 
appointed next week. He will regulate decrees for the social 
security reform approved by Congress late last year. 
  The reform was sponsored by Ramirez, who registered today as 
presidential candidate Andres Pastrana's ticket partner, and he 
immediately announced an ambitious and quick tour of Colombia. 
Ramirez was appointed labor minister in July 1992 on behalf of 
the New Democratic Force (FND), a conservative group founded by 
Pastrana, who announced a campaign and promised a government 
with supraparty leanings. 

</TEXT>

