<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havana Denounces Clinton's Call for Miami Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2103172394 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0100 GMT 19 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2103172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Pedro Otero from the "Evening Information </F>
Review" newscast] 
  [Excerpt] A few days ago, U.S. President William Clinton 
called for a summit meeting of American chiefs of state in 
Miami, Florida. He excluded Cuba from that invitation 
considering that Cuba does not meet the democratic requirements 
Washington has set for the rest of the area countries. So there 
will be a meeting without Cuba, the rebel member of the 
community. 
  Curiously, the call for a summit ignores the OAS, which 
because of its nature and purposes should be the one to promote 
such a summit, and ignoring them calls attention to a certain 
degree of speed and improvisation. 
  It has been said that the meeting will be on democracy, 
cooperation, and economy. In my opinion, this is an effort aimed 
at intruding in Iberio-American summit meetings or, at least, 
reducing the possibility of these summits working for unity and 
regional cooperation. 
  There is no doubt the Miami meeting has untrustworthy 
objectives. The United States tried to get invited to the first 
summit meeting of Ibero-American presidents in Guadalajara, 
Mexico, in 1991. It did not achieve its objective but it 
maintained its desire to be kept officially informed of what was 
discussed there. I do not know if it tried to do the same at the 
other summits, in Spain and Brazil. The White House has 
diminished the importance of what the Ibero-American chiefs of 
state said. What is clear is that the current call is aimed at 
reducing the significance of this movement, which will hold its 
fourth summit in Cartagena de Indias, Colombia, in June. 
  Once again Washington is marshalling its ability to try to 
divide our people with plans and projects that have nothing to 
do with our regional problems. We have been fooled for decades 
with dreams about development and well-being. Now, on the 
threshold of the 21st century, we are being told the same 
stories we were told last century to try and keep us separated. 
U.S. economic and military power has always obstructed Latin 
America's fair aspirations for unity. 
  At the Guadalajara summit, President Fidel Castro expressed 
caution about the so-far useless efforts to become an 
economically powerful and politically united community in spite 
of our huge resources and talent. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

