<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Onusal Chief Praises Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203040794 San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY in Spanish 21 Mar 
94 p 17 </F>

<F P=103> PA2203040794 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dr. Augusto Ramirez Ocampo, chief of the UN Mission 
for El Salvador (Onusal), said that "El Salvador should feel 
proud about its elections." The Onusal chief and his large team 
of observers toured the entire country on 19 and 20 March. 
Ramirez added that they had access to the latest information on 
what was transpiring "and, therefore, this was an 
extraordinarily normal election." 
  Ramirez described as "a Solomonic measure" the Supreme 
Electoral Tribunal [TSE] decision to install polling stations in 
Arcatao, San Jose las Flores, Nueva Trinidad, and San Isidro 
Labrador, because these four municipalities of Chalatenenango 
are considered to be refugees for former FMLN [Farabundo Marti 
National Liberation Front] combatants. 
  The voting started in those places at 1015 because ballot 
boxes were not transported until yesterday via Air Force 
helicopters after the TSE had a change of mind. The original 
plan was to install all ballot boxes in the city of 
Chalatenango, where 85 percent of the inhabitants of those four 
municipalities live. 
  Ramirez praised Salvadorans who stood in line without making 
any fuss to comply with their duties as citizens. He regretted 
delays in the voting process that prevented many people from 
voting. [as published] 
  The chief observer, of Colombian origin, recalled the 
commitment made by presidential candidates and secretaries 
general to President Cristiani to close polling stations at 1700 
only after every citizen still waiting to vote had cast his or 
her vote. 
  Ramirez said that Onusal will take note of all "anomalies, 
claims, and requests but will only report worthy ones. The 
atmosphere that has surrounded the peace process is yielding and 
will yield results," the chief of the observers added. 
  Among the small problems he noticed at certain voting sites 
were the delays in opening. In some cases, such as the Central 
American Pavillion of the International Fair Grounds, Ramirez 
intervened directly to expedite its opening. "In general, this 
was an extraordinarily normal election," the Colombian added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

