<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Electoral Tribunal Chief: Election Runoff Likely </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203050294 San Salvador Radio Cadena YSKL in Spanish 0400 
GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2203050294 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Cadena YSKL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Carlos Ramos] </F>
  [Text] Supreme Electoral Tribunal President Luis Arturo 
Zaldivar has noted that the initial results of Sunday's 
elections indicate a runoff election for president and vice 
president likely will be held within a month: 
  [Begin Zaldivar recording] There is an undeniable trend and 
everything seems to indicate there will be a presidential runoff 
election. The other elections will stand because it is [word 
indistinct] constitutional. At this time, current trends lead 
us to think there will be a runoff. I insist (?we do) what the 
law states -- namely, hold a runoff election. [end recording] 
  Zaldivar admitted that there were shortcomings in the 
balloting process, but he added that these will be corrected in 
the future to guarantee and improve similar electoral events: 
  [Begin Zaldivar recording] For example, the voting did not 
start at the time mandated by law. Many polling stations opened 
after 0700. This happened because this was the first time in 
the nation's history that the entire political spectrum was 
involved in one general election. Everyone wanted to serve as 
either president or secretary of the voting table boards. 
Delays were prompted by discussions along these lines among 
people who, according to the law, represented the various 
political parties. In some places, voting started after the 
scheduled time; nevertheless, everything settled down later, and 
I think everyone who wanted to vote did vote. [end recording] 
  Dr. Zaldivar pointed out that if there is indeed a runoff, 
steps will be taken to avert the same logistical problems 
encountered in Sunday's elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

