<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803220194 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803220194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Chile monitored through 17 
March. 
  According to the Central Bank's preliminary reports, the 
Chilean trade balance registered a $33.1 million deficit in 
January, with exports at $765 million and imports at $798.1 
million. This means the negative balance has been maintained for 
the ninth consecutive month. The country's purchase rate dropped 
4.5 percent and the sales rate increased 14 percent compared 
with the same month last year, a fact that Finance Minister 
Foxley regards as "good news." (Santiago LA TERCERA DE LA HORA 
in Spanish 24 Feb 94 Economic Section p 3) 
  Evaluating the economic performance in 1989-1993, Finance 
Minister Alejandro Foxley reported on 23 February that the 
economy grew 6 percent in 1993. He noted the GDP rose from $28.1 
billion in 1989 to $43.8 billion in 1993. Investment rose from 
$6.5 billion to $11.3 billion. He said government investments 
also increased from $760 million to $1.425 billion. He explained 
that the government's savings rose from $850 million in 1989 to 
$2.2 billion in 1993. This generated a fiscal surplus that 
increased from $506 million in 1989 to $890 million last year. 
Foxley said these results led the Chilean economy to grow four 
times faster than in developed countries and three times more 
quickly when compared with Latin American countries. (Santiago 
EL MERCURIO in Spanish 24 Feb 94 pp A1, A9) 
  The National Fishing Association reported Chile exported 
1.233 million metric tons of fishing products worth $1.172 
billion in 1993, a drop of 10 percent and 9.5 percent, 
respectively, compared with the previous year, when exports were 
1.370 million metric tons valued at $1.295 billion. (Santiago EL 
MERCURIO in Spanish 28 Feb 94 pp B1, B2) 
  The National Statistics Institute, INE, reported that the 
unemployment rate was 4.8 percent from November 1993 to January 
1994, an increase of 0.3 percent compared with the previous 
quarter, and a 0.4 percent increase compared with the November 
1992-January 1993 period. The labor force totalled 5,254,200 
people, an increase of 4.4 percent compared with the same 
quarter last year. The number of employees was 5,580,000, an 
increase of 3.9 percent compared with the same quarter in 1993. 
This means that 187,290 new jobs were created. (Santiago EL 
MERCURIO in Spanish 3 Mar 94 p B10) 
  The INE reported on 2 March that the February consumer price 
index was 0.3 percent, and that the cumulative inflation rate 
for the first two months of the year was 1.3 percent, and 13.1 
percent for the past 12 months. Housing increased 1.7 percent 
and transportation and communications 0.5 percent; food dropped 
1.2 percent and clothing 1.7 percent. (Santiago EL MERCURIO in 
Spanish 3 Mar 94 pp B1, B10) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

