<H3> <TI>   Union Representatives Meet With Aristide </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2103211694 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in Creole 1230 
GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2103211694 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Creole </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Within the scope of world efforts to resolve the 
Haitian crisis, union representatives are meeting with President 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide. A delegation from the unions left Haiti 
last week. The members of the crisis committee of the Haitian 
union organization met with Aristide on 19 March to seek a 
solution to the critical situation in Haiti. A member of this 
delegation labeled their first meeting with Aristide as very 
promising. Representatives of six Haitian union organizations -- 
including the General Independent Organization, Federation of 
Unionized Workers, Federation of Haitian Blue Collar Workers, 
and the two branches of the Autonomous Organization of Haitian 
Workers [CATH], including Mezyeux's CATH and Manuci Pierre's 
CATH -- were present. 
  Jean-Claude Lebrun, secretary general of CTH, the Federation 
of Haitian Workers, said that during this meeting discussions 
turned on how to create the conditions necessary to the lifting 
of the embargo. [passage omitted] 
  A second meeting between the union committee and President 
Aristide is scheduled for 21 March. The delegation that is to 
meet with President Aristide is now in Miami. 

</TEXT>

