<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803224794 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803224794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Bolivia monitored through 17 
March. 
  The annual balance of the mining and metal working 
industries 
issued by the Mining Secretariat shows that mining exports 
dropped 12 percent in 1993 compared with the previous year. 
Sales abroad totaled $366 million. (La Paz LA RAZON in Spanish 1 
Mar 94 p B4) 
  The revenues of the six state-run companies that will be 
privatized amounted to $1.060 billion in 1993. Bolivian 
Government Oil Deposits accounts for 59 percent of this total; 
Lloyd Boliviano Airlines 10 percent; and the remaining 30 
percent is distributed among the National Railway Enterprise, 
the National Telecommunications Enterprise, the National 
Electricity Enterprise, and the National Smelting Enterprise. 
(Santa Cruz EL MUNDO in Spanish 1 Mar 94 p 3) 
  The Minera del Sur Inc. Company, Comsur, this year will 
invest $30 million, including a $12.3 million credit recently 
granted by the World Bank, to promote mining operations in many 
parts of the country. Comsur, whose main shareholder is 
President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada, is planning to invest $26 
million in the Bolivar mine in Oruro. (Santa Cruz EL MUNDO in 
Spanish 1 Mar 94 p 1) 
  The Andean Development Corporation approved two loans for 
$98 
million for Bolivia. A $38 million loan was approved for the 
improvement of highways. Another $60 million loan was approved 
for financing investment projects and operating capital to 
foster productive activities in the farming, livestock, 
agro-industrial, industrial, mining, tourism, and services 
fields. (La Paz Radio Fides Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 17 Mar 
94) 
  Miguel Cirbian, Bolivian Government Oil Deposits exploration 
manager, reported that the new Los Kusis oil field discovered in 
Santa Cruz can initially produce 150 barrels per day. The field 
also can produce natural gas. (La Paz LA RAZON in Spanish 2 Mar 
94 p B2) 

</TEXT>

