<H3> <TI>   `Suspicious' Cars Near U.S. Envoy's Residence Were False 
Alarms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2103140194 Buenos Aires Radio Nacional Network in Spanish 
1330 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2103140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires Radio Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Two cars parked near the U.S. ambassador's residence 
in this capital caused concern among the police forces in charge 
of the security of U.S. Vice President Al Gore. The police bomb 
squad verified that both cases were false alarms. 
  The bomb squad acted a little after 0830 today when the 
police considered suspicious the presence of a Renault 18 pickup 
on Libertador Avenue with a flat tire. After a thorough check 
the police verified it was only a false alarm. A police 
tow-truck removed the car from near the ambassador's residence. 
  Soon afterward, the bomb squad returned to investigate a 
white Renault 12 parked on Libertador Avenue, 80 meters from the 
ambassador's residence and which had also called the attention 
of the police. After inspecting the car, the police verified 
that this was also a false alarm. 

</TEXT>

