<H3> <TI>   Funds Transferred to Catamarca To Alleviate Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803192994 Buenos Aires PAGINA/12 in Spanish 15 Mar 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires PAGINA/12 </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Daniel Victor Sosa] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Economy Ministry will transfer 50 million 
pesos to Catamarca to alleviate the effects of a very hard 
adjustment plan by which the province should eliminate, in two 
years, the public accounts in the red, which currently stand at 
$75 million annually. Deputy Governor Simon Hernandez has told 
PAGINA/12 that the commitments that were assumed under Decree 
349, signed by President Carlos Menem and Labor Minister Armando 
Caro Figueroa, "will entail no dismissals." However, a great 
many of the 23,000 provincial public servants are expected to be 
transferred through the sale of public enterprises. 
  The decree sets forth that the improvement of the province's 
fiscal and financial situation and the structural reform of the 
public sector will be implemented "in keeping with the economic 
policy guidelines that the national government has adopted on 
the subject." In this regard the Economy Ministry will in the 
next few hours transfer Treasury bonds for a nominal value of 70 
million pesos (the difference with the figure that the province 
will actually receive stems from the actual value of the bonds). 
  Acting Governor Hernandez -- Governor Arnaldo Castillo is on 
vacation -- said that the nation's contribution "was the 
condition we imposed for signing the fiscal pact. Another 
requirement that the Economy Ministry is fulfilling is the 
implementation of an investment program for 120 million pesos. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

