<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deal Increases Spanish Airline's Share in Aerolineas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803212694 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 18 
Mar 94 pp 1, 3 </F>

<F P=103> PY1803212694 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] (NA-DYN) -- The Argentine government and Iberia 
reached an agreement yesterday [17 March] on the future of 
Aerolineas Argentinas (ARSA) whereby the Spanish airline's 
shareholding is increased to 85 percent. 
  At a joint press conference attended by ARSA and Iberia 
executives, Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo said that the 
Spanish airline has made a 500 million dollar capital injection 
of which 100 million will go to reserves and the remaining 400 
million towards settling accrued debts. 
  The Argentine government in turn will hang on to 15 percent 
of the share packet of which 10 percent has been assigned to the 
employee shareholding programme. 
  The government will also authorize ARSA and any other 
airline 
that operates in Argentina to run its own aircraft servicing 
facilities and will restrict the availability of non-regular 
flights. 
  There will be no restriction on the number of flights on 
domestic routes. 
  ARSA will continue as a national flag carrier, a condition 
which the government has undertaken to defend should any 
protests arise from countries with which it has bilateral 
aerocommercial agreements and who object that Iberia owns more 
than 49 percent of ARSA. 
  At the same time the government is able to maintain its 
rights to veto even though its shareholding could sink below the 
five percent stipulated in the privatization process. 
  ARSA however no longer has the power to veto route 
management 
decisions or the investment plan. 
  After three years and four months of intrigue and failed 
discussions, yesterday's deal ironically takes the whole 
privatization process back to its first stage. The new share 
distribution is exactly the same as the original distribution 
made when ARSA was first privatized. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

