<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Agree to Principles on Telecommunications </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1903202094 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 18 Mar 
94 p 11 </F>

<F P=103> PY1903202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maria Helena Tachinardi from Brasilia] </F>
  [Excerpt] At the end of the First World Telecommunications 
Development Conference (WTDC/94) on 29 March, Brazil will sign a 
letter of principles on the expansion of international 
communications services. The Brazilian delegation that will 
attend the conference will be headed by Communications Minister 
Djalma de Moraes. Moraes, however, will not be present at the 
WTDC/94 opening ceremony on 21 March. 
  The conference will be opened by Argentine President Carlos 
Menem at the Sheraton Hotel in Buenos Aires. During the 
ceremony, U.S. Vice President Al Gore and ITU [International 
Telecommunications Union] Secretary General Pekka Tarjanne will 
deliver speeches. The conference's goal is to develop an overall 
strategy for telecommunications development for the year 2000. 
  The letter of principles, which already has been approved at 
the technical level by 183 member countries, is one of the ITU 
projects for the future. The ITU is a specialized UN agency that 
already has formed an international working group that deals 
with the reformulation of the international frequencies chart. 
Diplomat Flavio Sapha -- head of the communications minister's 
office -- reported that another of ITU's concerns is to organize 
the frequencies chart for cellular and satellite communications. 
He will leave for Buenos Aires this weekend accompanying the 
delegation comprised of Telebras [Brazilian Telecommunications, 
Inc.] President Adyr da Silva and members of the Foreign 
Ministry's Division for Transportation, Communications, and 
Services. 
  The Buenos Aires meeting will be in preparation for the 
Kyoto 
(Japan) plenipotentiary conference to be held in September. 
Brazilian entrepreneurs, including members of the Alcatel and 
Motorola companies, also will attend the Buenos Aires meeting, 
but only as observers, Sapha said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

