<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry To Discuss UN Council Expansion With G-7 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2203025594 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 21 Mar 
94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PY2203025594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maria Helena Tachinardi from Brasilia] </F>
  [Text] The Foreign Ministry will this week begin a series 
of contacts with industrialized countries, most of them members 
of the Group of Seven (G-7), to exchange ideas about expanding 
the UN Security Council and to find out how England, Italy, 
Sweden, Switzerland, Germany, France, Russian, Japan, the United 
States, and Canada view the possibility of granting Brazil a 
seat at the expanded UN Council. 
  U.S. Vice President Al Gore will meet President Itamar 
Franco 
at 1900 on 21 March, when he will sign with Foreign Minister 
Celso Amorim a protocol modifying the current framework 
agreement of scientific and technological cooperation between 
the two countries, thus making relations in this area more 
complex and aimed at high technology sectors. 

</TEXT>

