<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister: Government Believes Cuban Version of Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2103202094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1823 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2103202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 21 Mar (EFE) -- Today, Monday, 
Colombian Government Minister Fabio Villegas said that as long 
as there is no irrefutable proof on the alleged Colombian 
guerrilla summit in Havana, Colombia will continue to believe 
Cuba, which adamantly denies it. In the Caribbean city of 
Cartagena de Indias, the minister said: "What we know is that 
the Cuban Government is maintaining its former position, 
previously stated to our ambassador in Cuba, meaning the 
guerrilla summit was not held there." Villegas emphasized: "We 
believe that as long as we do not have enough evidence proving 
otherwise, we obviously have to believe the Cuban Government." 
  On Saturday, media sources reported that Cuban President 
Fidel Castro denied his government had sponsored a meeting of 
Colombian guerrilla leaders on the island. He reaffirmed his 
pledge to Colombia, in other words, to not interfere in its 
internal affairs. Castro ruled out the possibility various 
Colombian guerrilla leaders had participated in the Fourth Latin 
American and Caribbean Meeting for People's Solidarity and 
Self-Determination, held late in January in Havana. 
  The Colombian Government demanded an explanation from the 
Cuban Government on the alleged presence of Guerrilla 
Coordinating Board (CG) leaders in Cuba, and it warned that 
relations between the two countries would suffer a great setback 
if the rumor was confirmed. 
  Castro talked with Colombian Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin 
over the telephone and said he had ordered an investigation, 
while adding that he had individually verified all the names of 
the people who attended the solidarity meeting so he could 
guarantee with certainty that there were no guerrilla members. 
  On Thursday, Sanin said that based on information received 
from the Attorney General's Office, "we have serious evidence 
that Cuba possibly welcomed the guerrilla members, who 
apparently participated in a political summit." 

</TEXT>

