<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rio Group Foreign Ministers Continue Meeting </TI></H3>
<H4>   Issues Discussed at Meeting Reported </H4>
<F P=102> PY2303001594 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2303001594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Patricia Gomes from Brasilia] </F>
  [Text] The Rio Group today discussed in Brasilia the need 
to ensure the developing countries' access to high technology 
and the right to transfer it. 
  The 13 Rio Group foreign ministers will meet in Sao Paulo on 
22 and 23 April with a group of European Union foreign 
ministers. The meeting's objective will be to discuss proposals 
presented in the first Rio Group meeting this year, which ended 
today in Brasilia. 
  In the meeting, the foreign ministers discussed topics such 
as the fight against poverty, human rights, sustainable 
development, and science and technology exchange. 
  According to Foreign Minister Celso Amorim, the meeting 
helped the Rio Group member countries prepare for the 
presidential and chiefs of state meeting to be held in September. 
  The foreign ministers also analyzed the letter received from 
U.S. President Bill Clinton asking for a hemispheric conference 
to discuss poverty and misery in the American continent. 
  Minister Amorim also said the Rio Group member countries are 
concerned about the situation in Suriname, where armed groups 
conducted attacks a few days ago. 

</TEXT>

