<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803220694 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803220694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Peru monitored through 17 
March. 
  Education Vice Minister Esther Gago Hurtado and PRC 
Ambassador to Peru Chen Jiuchang on 5 March signed an agreement 
to promote a broad program of cultural exchange and strengthen 
links between the two countries. The program will be implemented 
through 1996. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 6 Mar 94 p 16) 
  The Japanese Government has agreed to lend Peru, together 
with the Inter-American Development Bank, IDB, $21 million to 
help improve health services. The agreement was signed on 16 
March by Prime and Foreign Minister Efrain Goldenberg and 
Japanese Deputy Foreign Minister (Shoko Atuma). Goldenberg said 
he hopes the loan will benefit at least 5 million Peruvians. 
(Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 0100 GMT 16 Mar 94) 
  Net profits for the Central Peru Mining Enterprise, 
Centromin, was $15 million in 1993. Sales domestically and 
abroad totaled $389 million. Although production increased $97.5 
million in 1993, sales dropped 3 percent compared with 1992 
because of a decline in international prices for the main 
minerals produced by Centromin. (Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 9 
Mar 94 p B1) 
  On 9 March, the Chilean and Peruvian agriculture ministers 
signed an economic, technical, and scientific cooperation 
agreement designed to protect regional llamas and vicunas. (Lima 
EXPRESO in Spanish 10 Mar 94 p A23) 

</TEXT>

