<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Storm Polling Center Seized by Opposition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203214994 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1618 GMT 22 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2203214994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 22 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Riot police this 
morning stormed a polling center that had been occupied by the 
opposition in Jucuapa Municipality in the eastern department of 
Usulutan. Opposition groups have accused the National 
Republican Alliance (Arena) government of committing fraud in 
Sunday's general elections. 
  Members and supporters of the Farabundo Marti National 
Liberation Front (FMLN), the Unity Movement, the National 
Conciliation Party (PCN), and Christian Democratic Party (PDC) 
yesterday occupied a school facility where ballot boxes were 
being stored. 
  FMLN member Ricardo Samayoa said riot police broke down the 
main entrance of the school while residents of Jucuapa, in the 
northern part of Usulutan, surrounded the building to prevent 
police from taking the ballot boxes to San Salvador. Samayoa 
added that no one was injured or beaten in the incident. He 
said members of the right-wing Arena party marked hundreds of 
ballots before voting began two days ago in nationwide general 
elections to elect a new president, mayors, and deputies. 
  "All of the political parties were able to confirm this. We 
found several Arena members with several marked ballots before 
the voting process began," he said. 
  The ballot boxes were being guarded by representatives of 
opposition political parties demanding that the Supreme 
Electoral Tribunal [TSE] annul the elections in this 
municipality in the eastern part of the country. They warned 
that if the TSE does not annul the elections in Jucuapa, those 
parties that took part in the elections in this region will 
elect a municipal government by consensus. The TSE has not 
issued a statement on this incident, which is unprecedented. 
  So far, the ruling Arena party has garnered 49.18 percent of 
the votes counted up until Monday afternoon to elect the 
president and vice president. The leftist coalition comprising 
the FMLN former guerrilla organization, Democratic Convergence 
(CD), and the National Revolutionary Movement (MNR) has obtained 
25.66 percent of the votes, while the PDC has obtained 15.94 
percent. The TSE has announced the possibility of a 24 April 
runoff in which the Arena and leftist coalition candidates will 
compete for the presidency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11514 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat056_f_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-056 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   FMLN Official Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203231894 San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU in Spanish 1230 
GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2203231894 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We have a last-minute report. Jucuapa riot police 
stormed the entrance of the Saul Flores School where the ballot 
boxes are located, according to members of the FMLN [Farabundo 
Marti National Liberation Front]. Ricardo Samayoa, of the FMLN 
Political Committee, said the people began to gather in front of 
the school building and added that there have not been any major 
incidents. 
  [Begin recording] [Samayoa] Riot police and members of the 
civilian National Police, whose actions are being repudiated by 
the residents of Jucuapa, broke into the school building where 
the election ballots were being held. This incident is evidence 
of the fraud that Arena [Nationalist Republican Alliance] has 
tried to stage in this town as well as in the rest of the 
country. The residents of Jucuapa are opposed to this. There 
have been clashes with members of the civilian National Police. 
We call on the international community to take note of the 
incident that is occurring at this time in the town of Jucuapa. 
  [Unidentified reporter] The ballot boxes have still not been 
taken to the Supreme Electoral Tribunal [TSE]? 
  [Samayoa] The ballot boxes are inside the building, but the 
entrance has been damaged. The locks have been destroyed and 
the door was damaged in an attempt to take out the ballot boxes. 
The people, however, have gathered there to prevent them from 
doing so and to observe what the riot police are doing. [end 
recording] 
  The police authorities have still not made a statement on 
the 
case. The TSE and the UN Observers for El Salvador had already 
challenged these votes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

