<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Financial Community `Does Not Hide' Support for Cardoso </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2203024594 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 21 
Mar 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PY2203024594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Getulio Bittencourt from New York] </F>
  [Text] During his trip to the United States last week, the 
last question asked of Finance Minister Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso elicited the only vague reply. So, will you run for the 
presidency of the Republic, Mr. Cardoso, or is it still a 
secret? "It is not a secret," he answered calmly, "but I still 
have to settle some things. I have not yet made up my mind." 
  The international financial community does not hide its 
preference for the finance minister as the next Brazilian 
president. Thomas J. Trebat, an executive manager from the 
Chemical Bank, contends that Cardoso is the best hope for the 
continuity of the present economic reforms under the next 
Brazilian president. 
  Tamzin Hobday, a Latin American expert at Baring Securities, 
cherishes the hope that a coalition among the PSDB [Brazilian 
Social Democracy Party], the PFL [Liberal Front Party], and the 
"ethical sector" from the PMDB [Brazilian Democratic Movement 
Party] will choose Cardoso as presidential candidate. Ed 
Cabrera, a Latin American expert at Merrill Lynch, believes that 
if Cardoso's stabilization program achieves a measure of success 
he will outpoll all the other candidates, heading a center-left 
coalition in the runoff elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

