<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803225494 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803225494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Brazil monitored through 17 
March. 
  The Brazilian Petroleum Corporation will invest $42.2 
million 
in 1994-97 to develop oil byproducts from the Marlim and 
Albacora oil fields located in the Campos Basin. It is expected 
that this program will generate approximately $1 billion in 
profits between 1995 and 2001. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 10 Mar 94 p 15) 
  On 9 March, British Treasury Secretary Michael Portillo met 
Brazilian Aeronautics Minister Lelio Viana Lobo to discuss the 
sale to Brazil of eight Rolls-Royce engines worth $100 million 
for three Boeing 777 planes. British Ambassador to Brazil Peter 
Heap said Transbrasil and the British company have not yet 
signed a sale contract but a letter of intent. (Sao Paulo GAZETA 
MERCANTIL in Portuguese 10 Mar 94 p 6) 
  On 9 March, President Itamar Franco signed a decree 
establishing two new free zones in the municipalities of 
Brasileia/Epitaciolandia and Cruzeiro do Sul, Acre State. A 
total of seven areas already have been placed under the special 
fiscal system in the country. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 10 Mar 94 p 6) 
  Rio Doce Valley Company's vice president, Anastacio Ubaldino 
Fernandes Filho, reported that the company is planning to trade 
future gold production in the international market, through 
which it expects to attract $180 million in foreign capital. 
Fernandes said the company is analyzing proposals by financial 
institutions to mediate in the operation. (Sao Paulo GAZETA 
MERCANTIL in Portuguese 10 Mar 94 pp 1-22) 
  Tax revenues increased 24 percent in February, a drop of 9 
percent compared with January, but an increase of 40.38 percent 
compared with the same month last year. (Sao Paulo GAZETA 
MERCANTIL in Portuguese 14 Mar 94 p 5) 
  Fuel prices were adjusted 19.5 percent as of 14 March. The 
prices of alcohol, gasoline, diesel oil, and cooking gas have 
increased 124.86 percent so far this year. The last 18.5 percent 
readjustment was decreed on 24 February. (Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO 
in Portuguese 15 Mar 94 p 21) 
  The Itamarati business group will invest $250 million in the 
next four years in a sugar cane project in Barra do Bugre, Mato 
Grosso State. The group owns 25,000 hectares of cultivated area 
in the region and a sugar mill currently producing 1 million 
sacks of sugar and 80 million liters of alcohol. (Sao Paulo 
GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 17 Mar 94 p 26) 

</TEXT>

