<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   SCD-1 Satellite Services To Expand in LA </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94SM0260B Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 10 Feb 
94 p A-16 </F>

<F P=103> 94SM0260B </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Julio Ottoboni] </F>
  [Text] Sao Jose dos Campos--In celebration of the Data 
Collection Satellite (SCD-1)'s first year in orbit, Minister of 
Science and Technology Jose Israel Vargas and the director of 
the National Institute of Space Research (INPE), Marcio Nogueira 
Barbosa, announced yesterday in Sao Jose dos Campos that the 
Brazilian satellite's services will be expanded to include 
scientific institutions in Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Bolivia 
that have already asked the Brazilian institute to install data 
collection platforms in their territories. Top INPE officials 
are meeting in Brasilia today with leaders from 10 African 
countries, also interested in using the satellite's resources. 
  According to Minister Israel Vargas, the Brazilian Space 
Agency, a civilian body, will circumvent the boycotts 
encountered by Brazil in the transfer of sensitive technology 
from the developed nations. "Our space program is strictly 
peaceful," he observed. 
  In the minister's opinion, the new space agency will enable 
Brazil to enter the low-altitude communications satellite 
market. "One of the agency's first assignments is to reexamine 
the entire Brazilian space program," he said. 
  At present, the Ministry of Science and Technology has 
signed 
major space cooperation agreements with China and is studying a 
partnership with Argentina. 

</TEXT>

