<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Approves Signing Geneva Protocol on Guerrillas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203203894 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2203203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] In a surprise move and after a long refusal, the 
Army has given its approval for Colombia to sign the Geneva 
Convention Protocol No. 2. The signing of this agreement grants 
the guerrillas the status of a belligerent force, and guarantees 
that the conflicts with the government will be ruled by 
international humanitarian law. Here is Monica Echeverry: 
  [Begin recording] [Echeverry] With a note sent by the 
defense 
minister and the Armed Forces commander to President Gaviria, 
Colombia accepts the signing of the Geneva Convention Protocol 
No. 2 following years of all-out opposition. Thus, Colombia 
acknowledges that it is in a state of war. 
  [Gustavo Rodriguez Vargas, member of the Foreign Ministry 
Advisory Commission] I believe it makes the conflict more real. 
The conflict is placed within parameters that at any given 
moment can be more manageable for a government. 
  [Echeverry] In addition to this, with the signing of 
Protocol 
No. 2, a code of ethics for war is established and the rebels 
are given the status of a belligerent force. The rebels must 
now accept the humanitarian law, which involves the presence of 
a UN overseeing group in the peace talks. The agreement must be 
presented to Congress, where it will be approved. Thus, the 
government moves a step ahead of Samper's star proposal to 
advance peace, and it also opens the doors for a new peace 
dialogue with the guerrillas. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

