<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Makes Changes to `Security Cabinet' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203214794 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1910 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2203214794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 22 Mar (DPA) -- Guatemalan President 
Ramiro de Leon Carpio made changes to his security cabinet in an 
attempt to resolve the high crime rate existing in the country, 
which consists of cases of theft, assaults, kidnappings, and 
other criminal activities. 
  The new government (interior) minister [El nuevo ministro de 
gobernacion interior] is Danilo Parinello, a former Constituent 
Assembly deputy, who said he accepted the post (considered to be 
the most difficult in the cabinet) because of his friendship 
with President Ramiro de Leon Carpio. He added that even though 
he has no experience in the area of security he will carry out 
the best possible actions. He announced the creation of an 
immediate reaction group to take care of emergencies that may 
appear. 
  Colonel Mario Alfredo Merida was appointed the new deputy 
government minister. He has experience in military 
intelligence. Former Justice of the Peace Salvador Figueroa was 
appointed police director. 
  The high crime rate is one of the leading problems 
confronting the government of Ramiro de Leon Carpio. Some 
sectors have pointed out that unemployment and extreme poverty 
suffered by the majority of the population are some of the 
reasons for the high crime rate. 

</TEXT>

