<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislator Criticizes U.S. Interference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2203004494 La Paz PRESENCIA in Spanish 11 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PY2203004494 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz PRESENCIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Chamber of Deputies Vice President Alfonso 
Ferrufino said yesterday that the use of violence as a method to 
fight the illegal drug trade has failed and now the United 
States must leave Bolivia alone to design its own antinarcotics 
strategy. 
  In the midst of growing tension in coca producing areas, 
legislators have again questioned official antinarcotics 
policies that emphasize repression as the main tool to fight 
trafficking. This is being blamed for the tension in Chapare. 
  "The results speak for themselves. The volumes of drugs 
introduced into the United States have increased and consumption 
has expanded during the years these policies have been in 
effect. This reality has forced Bill Clinton's administration 
to conclude that the drug problem in their country is a problem 
of education and health," Ferrufino said. 
  The legislator recognized that surplus coca plantations are 
linked to poverty and unemployment. The peasants have seen in 
that crop their only possibility for survival at a time of 
growing unemployment. 
  "If the United Nations understood and accepted the U.S. 
installation of radars to control the entry of drugs in its 
territory, why would the United States not accept that Bolivia 
wants to seek its own solution to the problem instead of 
continuing to implement a failure?" Ferrufino said. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

