<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havana Notes Arrest of Lucius Walker in Laredo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2203191294 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1000 
GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2203191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Religious leader Lucius Walker was recently released 
by police in Laredo after having been arrested together with 
Cuban-Canadian Camilo Garcia while they were trying to transport 
equipment across the border for Cuba. 
  Prior to Walker and Garcia's arrest, several members of the 
third U.S.-Cuba friendship caravan crossed the U.S.-Mexican 
border with a satellite communication system and several other 
electronic supplies. (Errol Edwards), coordinator of Pastors for 
Peace, stated that the significance of the event was not the 
fact of having transported the equipment from the United States 
to Mexico, but that it represented the weakening of the U.S. 
blockade against Cuba. 
  The members of the caravan, headed by Walker, returned to 
Laredo from Havana where they handed the Martin Luther King, 
Jr., Memorial Center a donation of more than 140 tons of 
humanitarian aid collected in more than 100 U.S., Canadian, and 
Mexican cities. 

</TEXT>

