<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Genie Murder Trail Continues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Deputy Minister To Testify </H4>
<F P=102> PA2303013694 Managua Radio Corporacion in Spanish 2300 GMT 
22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2303013694 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Corporacion </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Five O'Clock Sharp" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Deputy Foreign Minister Jose Bernard Pallais has 
been summoned to testify in the Jean Paul Genie murder trial. 
The judge advocate today summoned Pallais to testify as a 
witness in the trial against eight security escorts of General 
Humberto Ortega, chief of the Nicaraguan Army, for the murder of 
a young man in 1990. 
  At the time of the crime, Pallais was deputy government 
minister and was involved in the investigations, according to 
Judge Advocate Lieutenant Lester Gallo, who explained to Pallais 
the reasons behind his being called to testify. The military 
court last month opened the trial in connection with the death 
of Jean Paul Genie Lacayo, who was sprayed with gunfire when he 
attempted to drive past a military caravan along the road to 
Masaya on the outskirts of Managua. Gen. Humberto Ortega made 
statements [words indistinct] as a defendant, and, after the 
inquiry concluded, the judge advocate asked him not to leave 
Managua. This was interpreted by the press as a form of house 
arrest. The restraining order will be in force throughout the 
duration of the murder trial, which, according to defense 
attorney Mariano Barahona, could last anywhere from three weeks 
to more than a month. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Pallais is a member of the 
Tripartite 
Commission created by Violeta Chamorro's government to 
investigate the murders of former contras, which took place 
between 1990-1992 -- murders to which members of the EPS 
[Sandinist People's Army] have been linked. This commission 
also includes members of the Catholic Church and the OAS, and it 
has pointed its finger at the EPS as a violator of human rights 
in light of the fact that the EPS failed to try those soldiers 
allegedly responsible for the murders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

