<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203222194 </F>
<F P=103> PA2203222194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Panamanian economic developments monitored through 22 
March. 
  Francia de Sierra, director general of the Mineral Resources 
Directorate at the Ministry of Commerce and Industries, revealed 
the mining industry has invested $24 million this year, whereas 
in 1993 the investment was $5 million. Sierra added that 
production at the Santa Rosa mine, Canazas jurisdiction, 
Veraguas Province, will begin in June; this is expected to 
increase investments. Referring to the mining industry's 
future, she said a geologic study and an infrastructure 
inventory will be carried out in April. The study will cost 
between $10 million and $15 million and the cost of its 
feasibility study -- $450,000 -- will be paid with a donation 
from the Inter-American Development Bank. (Panama City LA PRENSA 
in Spanish 9 Mar 94 p 11A) 
  ``Delia de De Castro, director general of domestic trade,'' 
reported 556 licenses with an invested capital of $1,674,500 
were issued in January. She added that this represents $20,401 
in taxes. She said this is a 15 percent increase compared with 
January 1993, when the Ministry issued 480 permits for an 
invested capital of $1,909,650. (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA 
in Spanish 15 Mar 94 p 11A) 
  The Panamanian Government has approved Executive Decree No. 
19 to confirm a 23 cent discount in the tariff for each box of 
bananas exported in 1994. The report adds that 38,255,291 boxes 
of bananas were exported in 1993, thus allowing the discount 
anticipated in Article 1 of Law 16, dated 18 June 1993. (Panama 
City LA PRENSA in Spanish 20 Mar 94 p 2) 
  Ricardo Duran, president of the Panamanian Chamber of 
Commerce, Industries, and Agriculture, has stated that growth 
levels will continue to rise although the country is engaged in 
an electoral process. A survey conducted by the chamber's 
Studies Center states the Panamanian economy registered stable 
growth levels, and the GNP attained a 6.6 percent growth rate. 
(Panama City EL SIGLO in Spanish 21 Mar 94 p 2) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

