<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Admits Deadline for Approving Patents Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2203135994 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1145 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2203135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 22 Mar (NA) -- Foreign Ministry 
Secretary General Andres Cisneros has implicitly accepted the 
existence of a 30-April deadline imposed by the United States 
for Argentina to approve a new law on pharmaceutical patents. 
  Cisneros explained that U.S. laws "do not contain deadlines, 
but mechanisms for presenting proposals," admitting, however, 
that 30 April is the date foreseen in this mechanism. 
  The official said dates "are not arbitrarily set by U.S. 
executive officials." They are part of U.S. laws. 
  Cisneros explained that these laws "do not establish 
deadlines, but provide mechanisms and certain dates for 
submitting proposals." 
  The Foreign Ministry secretary said U.S. laws contemplate 
economic sanctions against Argentina if a new law on 
pharmaceutical patents is not approved within the established 
period. 
  Cisneros said the Argentine Government "will respond to this 
pressure, defending the country's interests." Cisneros added 
that the new law will not "solely respond to foreign pressure, 
but also to Argentina's national interests." 
  "U.S. Government and Argentine interests are not necessarily 
incompatible. Compatibility ends when interests become 
incongruous," Cisneros warned. 
  "This is not being difficult or different from what is being 
done by other Western economies in similar situations," Cisneros 
said, adding: "We are not doing anything different from what was 
done within the GATT." 
  Regarding the possibilities of the bill's approval by 
Congress, Cisneros said: "We do not see any problems." He 
added: "Congress will approve the measure when legislators think 
our national interests are served." Cisneros admitted that it 
will be very difficult to get a new law approved by the last day 
of next month. 
  "Economic sanctions are not good, but Argentina handles its 
own schedule for approving laws and pursues its own interests." 
  Cisneros confessed that U.S. Vice President Albert Gore 
received a sort of promise that the bill will finally be 
approved because the Government "must draft and send the bill 
and then get it approved." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

