<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Camacho Solis Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2203235594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2255 GMT 22 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2203235594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 22 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Manuel Camacho 
Solis, government commissioner for peace and reconciliation in 
Chiapas, denied today that he seeks to be a presidential 
candidate in the upcoming 21 August general elections. 
  Local newspaper reports had reported the possibility that 
Camacho might be one of the contenders in view of his primary 
role in the Chiapas peace process and that political analysts 
had included him in the list of "presidential hopefuls." 
  "The decision I am making might disappoint some people, but 
I 
am certain that they would reproach me if I were to place any 
other interest above the topic of peace," Camacho stated in 
statements to newsmen. He also dismissed the possibility of 
occupying a Senate seat and said he will dedicate his efforts to 
peace in Chiapas, where an armed group occupied several towns 
and attacked a garrison early this year, prompting the Mexican 
Army to step in. 
  Camacho was appointed by President Carlos Salinas de Gortari 
as commissioner for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas on 10 
January. After intense negotiations he achieved a preliminary 
agreement which will be analyzed by the government and the armed 
group. 
  "Without this (political) definition, it would be difficult 
to continue my work in favor of peace in Chiapas," Camacho 
added. His position is independent of the government [words 
indistinct] refusal to participate in the elections. The 
commissioner noted that "if it is noted that my priorities 
include being a presidential candidate, it could harm the peace 
process" in Chiapas where over 100 persons were killed. 
  Some 42 million voters, a little less than half of the 
country's population, will go to the polls on 21 August to elect 
a new president, new deputies, and part of the Senate. 
  The candidates in the elections will be Luis Donaldo Colosio 
of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, Diego Fernandez 
de Cevallos of the National Action Party, and Cuauhtemoc 
Cardenas of the Party of the Democratic Revolution. There are 
two female candidates: Cecilia Soto of the Labor Party and 
Marcela Lombardo of the Popular Socialist Party. Other hopefuls 
are Rafael Aguilar of the Cardenist Front for National 
Reconstruction Party, Pablo Emilio Madero of the National 
Opposition National Union, Alvaro Perez of the Authentic Party 
of the Mexican Revolution, and Jorge Gonzalez of the Ecologist 
Party of Mexico. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

