<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agriculture Secretary Notes Need for Self-Sufficiency in Food </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2303022094 Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 18 Mar 94 p 54 </F>
<F P=103> PA2303022094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City LA JORNADA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Antonio Quevedo Susunaga] </F>
  [Excerpt] Culiacan Rosales, Sinaloa, 17 Mar -- Agriculture 
and Hydraulic Resources Secretary Carlos Hank Gonzalez has 
cautioned, "Mexico must become self-sufficient in food because 
it would be very dangerous to have to depend on another country, 
even if it is a friendly country." The secretary issued this 
warning during his speech at the ceremony in which Jorge Kondo 
Lopez, a state leader of the Federation of Agricultural 
Associations of Sinaloa State, presented his second work report. 
  Hank said, "Self-sufficiency in food means producing what is 
necessary to feed our country." He recalled that four years 
ago, Mexico had to import beans, and that this was very 
difficult to do because of international shortages. 
  He said: "We do not want the country swamped with foreign 
products; we must import only what we need." He said that 
although at this moment it is advantageous to import basic 
materials, machinery, and seeds, the ideal situation would be to 
not require any imports. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11606 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat056_c_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
