<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sao Paulo Prefect Maluf To Run for President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2203141894 Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 19 
Mar 94 Section 1 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> PY2203141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Carlos Eduardo Alves] </F>
  [Excerpt] Sao Paulo Prefect Paulo Maluf told the leadership 
of the PPR [Progressive Renewal Party] yesterday that he will be 
a presidential candidate in the elections to replace President 
Itamar Franco. "I will be a candidate, I will leave the 
prefecture on 30 March and I expect everyone's help" said Maluf 
during a three-hour meeting in his house in Sao Paulo. Maluf 
seeks to end the pressure from friends and relatives not to run 
for president. 
  Senator Esperidiao Amin (SC) [Santa Catarina], national 
president of the PPR, made the announcement. He said: "I am 
convinced Maluf will be our presidential candidate." A good 
part of the meeting was used to evaluate the studies of Maluf's 
electoral possibilities and of the PPR candidates for state 
governors. 
  One point emphasized by Maluf was the concentration of his 
support, as shown in the polls, in the middle, lower middle, and 
lower classes of the population which cover the largest part of 
the electorate. The evaluation of the PPR is that Finance 
Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso (PSDB) [Brazilian Social 
Democracy Party] who would be Maluf's direct competitor in a 
second round would have problems getting the votes of the poor. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

