<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Promulgates Capitalization Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2203191394 La Paz Television Nacional Network in Spanish 
1700 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2203191394 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Television Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Passage omitted] President Gonzalo Sanchez de 
Lozada promulgated the capitalization law yesterday. It becomes 
effective upon its publication in the official gazette. 
  The sore point is that the opposition has filed, or will do 
in the next few hours, a petition with the Supreme Court to 
declare the law unconstitutional. The problem is one of 
interpretation. 
  [Begin recording] [Deputy Edil Sandoval] The petition of 
unconstitutionality is presented against resolutions that 
violate the Constitution or affect the interests of one or more 
individuals. If the Supreme Court admits the petition, which I 
do not believe it will, and decides in favor of the petition, 
such decision will only benefit those who signed the petition. 
Therefore, in the worst of cases the decision will not 
invalidate the law. [passage omitted] 
  [Deputy Carlos Borth] The Constitution also grants deputies 
the right to make this type of petitions in special cases. Let 
us recall that the capitalization law regulates the transfer of 
five enterprises to the private sector. We, the MIR [Movement 
of the Revolutionary Left], will specifically oppose the 
transfer of YPFB [Bolivian Government Oil Deposit] [passage 
omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

