<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Burelli Comments on Move </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2403031894 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2403031894 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" Newscast] </F>
  [Text] As for foreign relations, the Venezuelan Government 
today decided to withdraw Foreign Minister Miguel Angel 
Burelli's candidacy for OAS secretary general. 
  [Being Burelli recording] As unusual practices developed 
during the elections, the OAS's spirit of equality and democracy 
was exceeded. The OAS has always maintained the alternation or 
rotation principle, by which a country, regardless of how 
honorable its aspirations are, should not occupy the OAS post if 
that country has already occupied it in the past. Such an 
attitude would be detrimental to those nations that have never 
occupied it. 
  Of course, this attitude does not mean that the merits of 
the 
other candidates for this post should not be recognized. On 
those grounds, to continue serving the hemispheric cause with 
dignity, which is definitely important, the national government 
makes public the withdrawal of its candidacy for OAS secretary 
general, because there are no concrete objections to the 
autonomy of the elections. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

