<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   ARENA Candidate `Ready To Defeat' Leftists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2303143694 San Salvador Radio Cadena YSKL in Spanish 1730 
GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2303143694 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Cadena YSKL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Wilfredo Cordoba from the "KL Radio News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Armando Calderon Sol, presidential candidate for the 
Nationalist Republican Alliance [ARENA], said a few minutes ago 
that he is ready to defeat the leftist coalition in a runoff 
election and added that he is unafraid of facing a 
centrist-leftist coalition. The politician also mentioned the 
irregularities that emerged in last Sunday's elections. 
  [Begin recording] [Calderon Sol] It has been proven that the 
Salvadoran people do not want the radical left. It has been a 
vote to reject them. I do believe they have won a political 
opening for democratic opposition and an opportunity to 
demonstrate their adherence to the system. We hope they can 
finally join the country's political life. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Is there going to be a vote recount? 
Are you going to call for a vote recount to see if you can 
[words indistinct]? 
  [Calderon Sol] We are not interested in discussing the first 
round. If a runoff election is needed, we will support it 
because we want a clear, impressive, and marvelous mandate. We 
know we are going to have 70 percent support or more, perhaps 75 
percent. It is going to be a clear, definitive, five-year 
mandate. 
  [Reporter] What were the most serious problems surrounding 
the elections? 
  [Calderon Sol] I believe it was the situation at the voting 
centers, the lack of information for voters, and the logistics 
problems that existed that day. The real problem was the lack 
of information for voters. 
  [Reporter] [Question indistinct] 
  [Calderon Sol] On the contrary, we have a month to tell the 
truth to the Salvadoran people. I believe the Supreme Electoral 
Tribunal will be forced to do an evaluation and correct the 
mistakes that were made. That way we can have a massive turnout 
in the next elections, and I am sure that all the Salvadoran 
people will accompany us. [end recording] 
  That was a portion of the statements made by Dr. Armando 
Calderon Sol, presidential candidate for the ruling ARENA. 
Meanwhile, at the vote counting center, there is speculation 
about the number of deputies' seats that could have been won by 
the various political parties after certain percentages were 
made known. According to unofficial figures made available so 
far, ARENA would have obtained 40 deputies; the FMLN, 20 
deputies; the Christian Democratic Party, 16 deputies; 
Democratic Convergence, three deputies; the National 
Conciliation Party, three deputies; and the Unity Movement, one 
deputy. These are unofficial figures that could change once the 
total number of votes obtained from each of the departments is 
made available. 

</TEXT>

