<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Minister Explains Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2303151094 Managua Radio Nicaragua Network in Spanish 1200 
GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2303151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Nicaragua Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "This Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Deputy Foreign Minister Jose Bernard Pallais has 
repeated the testimony he gave under oath at the 7th Criminal 
Court, which was in charge of the preliminary investigation of 
the murder of Jean Paul Genie, who was shot to death on 28 
October 1990. 
  Dr. Pallais, who was deputy government minister at the time 
and in charge of public security, was subpoenaed to testify on 
Tuesday afternoon before the military judge, First Lieutenant 
Lester Gallo Sandoval. Pallais confirmed that, upon 
instructions from the government, he and high-ranking Police 
officers took over the investigation in connection with this 
case. 
  [Begin recording] [Pallais] Yes, I was summoned by the 
president of the Republic to participate in a meeting two or 
three days after the death. During the meeting I was told about 
the importance of this case because the victim's father had 
information that led him to believe it was possible that the 
shots came from a military motorcade. Consequently, and given 
that rumors... 
  [Unidentified reporter, interrupting] Doctor, did you... 
  [Pallais, interrupting] Given the rumors circulating which 
implied that the motorcade was led by Army General Humberto 
Ortega, I was instructed to supervise the investigations that 
the National Police had begun and to maintain close contacts 
with Mr. Genie so he would trust that justice would prevail and 
would therefore be inclined to cooperate in the investigation by 
giving the names of witnesses whom he had identified and who 
said they were afraid to testify. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

