<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Views Scope </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2403030194 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 0016 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2403030194 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Many members of the Executive Branch have said that 
the possibility of the Congress granting the president special 
powers by way of a law is interesting. Interior Minister Ramon 
Escovar Salom said the government should wait for the proposal 
to mature and be presented before making any official 
announcement. He said, however, that the government will not 
shy away from any responsibility handed down by the Legislative 
Branch. He stressed that the country's problems are not 
exclusively economic or financial. 
  [Begin recording] [Escovar] We would first have to see what 
exactly the scope of these powers will be. It would make more 
sense for these powers to allow the Executive Branch to deal 
with all aspects of the crisis, and to attack them with the 
swiftness and timeliness the nation demands. [end recording] 
  Ramon Escovar Salom pointed out that the proposal came from 
the Congress and not from Executive Branch. Nevertheless, he 
said the government cannot refuse to study the idea. 

</TEXT>

