<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colosio Shot, Killed in Attack During Tijuana Campaign Stop </TI></H3>
<H4>   Investors Urged Not To Abandon Market </H4>
<F P=102> PA2403144994 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1234 
GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2403144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Elizabeth Diaz Otero] </F>
  [Text] Luis German Carcova, president of the Business 
Coordinating Council, has made a spirited appeal to foreign 
investors not to withdraw from the Mexican Stock Market -- a 
most volatile market. 
  The council has urged national and foreign investors who 
have 
capital investments in Mexico to remain calm and not to make 
hasty decisions. Luis German Carcova said the best way to 
demonstrate a love for the country is to confront the situation 
and to keep working. 
  [Begin Carcova recording] We ask them to remain calm and to 
look at and analyze the situation carefully. We have to 
determine within the next few hours how to best face this 
situation. I am certain we will be able to resolve this 
situation and that the Mexican people will continue to move 
ahead. No one can stop us, and no one will. 
  We ask them to remain calm and not to make hasty decisions. 
This is a time to demonstrate maturity and love for our 
country. One of the best ways businessmen and investors can 
demonstrate this love is by not splitting up, but, as the saying 
goes, by sticking to their guns -- namely, work, investments, 
and the generation of wealth and jobs. [end recording] 
  Carcova said he is angry about the assassination of Luis 
Donaldo Colosio. [words indistinct] a leader of organized 
businessmen, has said that in Mexico there are groups interested 
in destabilizing the nation. The murder of Luis Donaldo Colosio 
is clear evidence of this, he said. 
  In an interview at Los Pinos, Manuel Robleda, president of 
the Mexican Stock Market, did not want, or was unable, to 
predict what repercussions this event might have on the stock 
market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

