<H3> <TI>   Paper Lists Chamber Election Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2403041194 Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 15 Mar 
94 p 9a </F>

<F P=103> PA2403041194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Official Results of the Chamber of Representatives 
election. 
<H5>  Liberals Maintain Majority. </H5>
  In certain regions of the country seats were decided by two 
to five votes. The ruling party defeated the Conservative Party 
by about 1.2 million votes nationwide. There was scarce voting 
for candidates from Indian communities. The participation of 
Christians increased. 
<H5>  Amazonas </H5>
  With 100 percent of the voting tables counted: 
  Juan Jose Silva, Independent Civic Movement, 2,104 votes. 
  Alvaro Ayala, Liberal Party, 1,351. 
<H5>  Antioquia </H5>

  With 98 percent of the voting tables counted: 
  Ramon Elejalde Arbelaez, Liberal, 33,230. 
  Ernesto Mesa Arango, Liberal, 29,091. 
  Gabriel Zapata, New Democratic Force [NFD], 28,363. 
  Benjamin Higuita, Conservative Party, 25,666. 
  Humberto Tejada, Conservative, 21,867. 
  Juan Ignacio Castrillo, NFD, 19,588. 
  William Velez Mesa, Liberal, 18,240. 
  Luis Norberto Guerra, Conservative, 18,092. 
  Manuel Ramiro Velasquez, Conservative, 17,284. 
  Gustavo Lopez Cortes, NFD, 17,280. 
  Evelio Ramirez, Liberal, 16,399. 
  Roberto Herrera, Liberal, 16,143. 
  Luis Fernando Duque, Liberal, 16,050. 
  Guillermo Gaviria, Liberal, 13,249. 
  Arlen Uribe Marquez, Liberal, 12,696. 
  Rodrigo Echeverri, Liberal, 12,387. 
  Barlahan Henao, Liberal, 11,829. 
<H5>  Arauca </H5>
  With 82.9 percent of the voting tables counted: 
  Adalberto Jaimes Ochoa, Liberal, 12,680. 
  Julio Acosta Bernal, Liberal, 7,434. 
<H5>  Altantico </H5>

  With 98 percent of the voting tables counted: 
  Ines Gomez, People's Will [Voluntad Popular], 38,771. 
  Mario Varon, Conservative, 36,705. 
  Tarquino Pacheco, People's Will, 32,910. 
  Jose Llinas, Liberal, 24,905. 
