<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political, Military Figures Comment on Wage Increase </TI></H3>
<H4>   Senate Charges Government Fomenting Crisis </H4>
<F P=102> PY2403002694 Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 23 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PY2403002694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Senate released a communique on 22 March 
charging that the government is using the media to foment the 
crisis among the three branches of government, a crisis prompted 
by the conversion of salaries into the URV [Real Value Unit] 
system on 20 March. According to the communique, the state of 
democratic law does not allow a confrontation among the branches 
of the Republic "under penalty of an institutional crisis of 
serious internal and external consequences." 
  In the following paragraph, the Senate notes that it is 
appropriate for the press to criticize or praise the actions of 
the three branches of government and correct possible mistakes. 
The communique says: "It is not correct, however, to use the 
media to foment animosities that may compromise the 
institutions." 
  The communique also recalls that Congress did not fail to 
support the government, and approved the economic program. The 
communique, signed by Congress President Senator Humberto Lucena 
(PMDB-PB [Brazilian Democratic Movement Party-Paraiba State]), 
notes that nothing will justify a diversion from championing the 
"system of responsible rights, our country's supreme legal and 
social good, rights that are actually based on respect for 
independence and harmony among the three branches of 
government." The communique concludes with a call for common 
sense to prevail, with negotiations by the president of the 
Republic, "who, under a presidential system of government, is 
entitled to conduct our country's political-administrative 
process." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

