<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2403211694 </F>
<F P=103> PY2403211694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Chile monitored through 24 
March. 
  The Swedish Government on 10 March donated $5 million to 
Bolivia. This money will be used to pay a debt to the World 
Bank. The agreement was signed by Bolivian Foreign Minister 
Antonio Aranibar and Swedish Ambassador to Bolivia Lars 
Schonander at the Foreign Ministry. (La Paz PRESENCIA in Spanish 
11 Mar 94 p 1) 
  The World Bank will grant $94 million to Bolivia in June. Of 
this, $50 million will be designed for the general budget and to 
help the government face transition costs. The remainder will be 
earmarked for the hydrocarbons industry, the Bolivian Government 
Oil Deposits privatization project, and for technical assistance 
to the National Electricity Enterprise. (Santa Cruz EL MUNDO in 
Spanish 11 Mar 94 National Page p 1) 
  Pension fund administration boards' profits were $2.4616 
billion in 1993, a drop of 46 percent compared with 1992. Last 
year, six of the 13 boards had losses, compared with two in 
1992. Santiago Inc. registered the highest deficit with $218.6 
million. (Santiago ESTRATEGIA in Spanish 10 Mar 94 p 16) 
  The Central Bank of Chile termed 1993's economic results 
satisfactory. Economic growth was 6 percent last year. 
Construction, commerce, and transportation were the most dynamic 
sectors. Investment hit a record 27 percent. Production in 1993 
totaled $43.6 billion. (Santiago Television Nacional de Chile 
Imagen Internacional in Spanish 0100 GMT 24 Mar 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
